Vorbis metadata, called Vorbis comments, supports metadata tags similar to those implemented in the ID3 standard for MP3. The metadata is stored in a vector of byte strings of arbitrary length and size. The size of the vector and the size of each string in bytes is limited to 232 − 1 (about 4.3 billion, or any positive integer that can be expressed in 32 bits). oofer_dww 30/07/2022 19:23
nonfree ffmpeg builds with fdk_aac: 32-bit: https://github.com/AnimMouse/ffmpeg-autobuild/releases/download/m-2022-02-22-19-31/ffmpeg-0aa7142-8b4e4ea-win32-nonfree.7z 64-bit: https://github.com/AnimMouse/ffmpeg-autobuild/releases/download/m-2022-02-22-19-31/ffmpeg-0aa7142-8b4e4ea-win64-nonfree.7z (last compatible builds on windows 7) if you're encoding your music with aac under ffmpeg, do not use the regular binaries, as they only have ffmpeg's not so great aac encoder(which seems to not do he-aac) to use the fdk_aac library, you must specify it in the command line, example: ffmpeg -i input.flac -c:a libfdk_aac -b:a 128k output.m4a this will encode aac using the fdk library at 128 kbps bitrate. this encoder also allows for encoding he-aac and he-aac v2 ffmpeg -i input.flac -c:a libfdk_aac -profile:a aac_he -b:a 64k output.m4a this will encode he-aac at 64 kbps bitrate(delivers nearly same quality as regular aac at half the bitrate) ffmpeg -i input.flac -c:a libfdk_aac -profile:a aac_he_v2 -b:a 32k output.m4a this will encode he-aac v2 at 32 kbps bitrate(designed for really low bitrates only, no point in going above 56 kbps bitrate with this one, use he-aac for that instead) he-aac v2 only handles stereo if your source contains a cover, you will need to add the parameter -vcodec copy to keep it, if you don't want to keep it, add -vn instead (edited)
